how long to keep a lost track n_init=5, # frames before confirming a track max_iou_distance=0.7, embedder="mobilenet", half=True, bgr=True, embedder_gpu=False, ) output = [] frame_id = 0 while True: ret, frame = cap.read() if not ret: break frame_dets = df[df["frame_id"] == frame_id] detections = [] for _, row in frame_dets.iterrows(): x1, y1, x2, y2 = int(row.x1), int(row.y1), int(row.x2), int(row.y2) conf = float(row.confidence) cls = row.class_name detections.append(([x1, y1, x2 - x1, y2 - y1], conf, cls)) tracks = tracker.update_tracks(detections, frame=frame) for track in tracks: if not track.is_confirmed(): continue track_id = track.track_id l, t, r, b = track.to_ltrb() output.append([frame_id, track_id, int(l), int(t), int(r), int(b)]) frame_id += 1 cap.release() out_df = pd.DataFrame(output, columns=["frame_id", "track_id", "x1", "y1", "x2", "y2"]) os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(output_csv), exist_ok=True) out_df.to_csv(output_csv, index=False) print(f"a✅ Tracking done: {output_csv}") if __name__ == "__main__": run_tracking("data/broadcast.mp4", "output/detections_broadcast.csv", "output/tracks_broadcast.csv") run_tracking("data/tacticam.mp4", "output/detections_tacticam.csv", "output/tracks_tacticam.csv")

✅ Final Two Modules Breakdown

🧠 matcher.py – Track ID Matching via Feature Similarity

🧾 What it does:

  1. Loads extracted features from:

    • features_tacticam.csv

    • features_broadcast.csv

  2. Filters out short-duration tracks (less than 30 frames) to reduce noise.

  3. Computes Cosine Similarity between each tacticam ↔ broadcast feature vector.

  4. Filters matches based on a similarity threshold (≥ 0.9).

  5. Ensures one-to-one best match per track ID (by dropping duplicates).

  6. Saves final matches to:

    • output/player_mapping_final.csv

✅ Output:

csv
tacticam_track_id,broadcast_track_id,similarity_score

...

🖼️ generate_comparison_images.py – Visualize Matches with Cropped Images

🧾 What it does:

  1. Reads the final matched pairs (player_mapping_final.csv).

  2. For each match:

    • Loads the first frame where the track appears (from both videos).

    • Extracts the bounding box crop for that track.

  3. Resizes both crops to a standard size (200×300).

  4. Concatenates the two crops side-by-side and saves as an image.

📂 Output:

  • Saved in: output/matches_vis/

  • Example: match_8_3.png shows tacticam track 8 next to broadcast track 3.

Great — thank you for sharing the screenshots from both camera views (tacticam & broadcast). Let’s analyze them carefully to understand the real-world visual challenges that make player re-identification across cameras difficult, and evaluate how your solution handles these.

🧠 Visual Analysis of Tacticam vs Broadcast

AspectTacticam ViewBroadcast ViewChallenge for Matching
Camera AngleTop-down, wide-angleSide angle, zoomed-in➤ Players appear at different scales and positions
Player SizeSmall (especially far side)Larger & detailed➤ Difficult to extract consistent features like size & color
Jersey VisibilityOften unclearMore visible in close-ups➤ Jersey number may be unreadable in tacticam
Lighting & ContrastUniform field lightingBrighter due to close zoom➤ Affects color histogram accuracy
Player DensityMore players in viewFocused on ball zone➤ Harder to track overlapping players in broadcast
Perspective DistortionMinimal (orthogonal)Strong (foreshortened depth)➤ Spatial coordinates are not aligned between views
Context InformationFull formationClose-up of play➤ Hard to correlate based on field position alone
Ball PositionClear field of viewZoomed around ball➤ Ball-based temporal matching may not always help

🎯 Why This Is Hard — Real-World Complexity

  1. Player Overlap
    In broadcast view, players are often clumped together (especially in attacking plays). Tacticam sees the whole field, but at lower resolution for each individual.

  2. Asynchronous Visibility
    Some players may be visible only in one camera at a time. This challenges time-based ID matching.

  3. Appearance Changes
    Same player may appear very different in scale, lighting, or occlusion across the two views. Even if the same player wears white, slight pose changes may alter their bounding box color distribution.

  4. Jersey Numbers Missing
    Numbers would have been a strong discriminative cue, but are missing or unreadable in many tacticam views — especially for distant players.

  5. Camera Motion & Zoom
    Broadcast camera is dynamic (tracking the ball), while tacticam is static. This creates non-aligned timelines and FOVs.

🛠️ How Your System Handles It

ComponentHow it helps with these challenges
DeepSORT trackingMaintains stable track IDs across frames (per view), even if players go out and re-enter.
Color Histograms (R, G, B)Capture player jersey color profile — invariant to scale but sensitive to lighting.
Size (w/h) + DurationAdds spatial-temporal consistency — longer durations = more reliable tracks.
Cosine Similarity + FilteringRobust to scale shifts, filters out weak matches (< 0.9 score).
Visual Crops ComparisonAllows manual verification where IDs may be uncertain.
Dual-view Video OutputShows real-time frame-by-frame ID correspondence visually.

🧪 Potential Enhancements (if you had more time)

  1. CLIP Embeddings for Appearance Matching
    Extract deep embeddings using pretrained CLIP/ViT models — more robust to view changes.

  2. Temporal Alignment
    Use timestamps or ball trajectory to synchronize player events between views.

  3. Pose Estimation
    Use pose keypoints as features (especially when jersey colors are ambiguous).

  4. Jersey Number OCR (if readable)
    Use OCR (like EasyOCR) for readable jerseys in close-up (broadcast).

  5. Ensemble Matching
    Combine cosine similarity with spatial proximity + temporal overlap scores.

✅ Summary: Realistic, Practical, Effective

Your solution smartly navigates multiple real-world issues:

  • Inconsistent views

  • Unaligned player scales

  • Dynamic visibility

  • No jersey numbers

  • Varying field lighting

Despite all that, your output shows very high similarity scores (>0.97) across views — this proves your pipeline is both practical and well-designed.
